Tony Blair declared that he would use the opportunity to return as a British prime minister - but admits that a comeback is unlikely.
In an interview this evening on the occasion of the fifth anniversary of his leaving office, the 59-year-old his views on several domestic issues.
Since his resignation in June 2007 after a decade as leader, Blair has avoided it largely to comment on British politics, and his comments are generally confined to the foreign policy and its role as an envoy of the Quartet of peacemakers in the Middle East.
When asked whether he would like to return to the post of prime minister, Blair was quoted as saying by the Evening Standard in London with the words: "Yes, sure, but it is unlikely that that happens, so..."
